Unsupervised protein embeddings outperform hand-crafted sequence and structure features at predicting molecular function

Amelia Villegas-Morcillo, Stavros Makrodimitris, Roeland C.H.J. van Ham, Angel M. Gomez, Victoria Sanchez and Marcel J.T. Reinders

Data

Protein Data Bank

  • redundant sequences removed(identity threshold - \(95\%\))
  • \(11~749\) protein chains
  • \(5\)-fold CV with additional sampling to validation data

SwissProt

  • \(80~176\) protein sequences
  • train/validation/test split (\(80\%/10\%/10\%\))

CAFA3

  • train/validation/test split (\(80\%/10\%/10\%\))
  • \(63~994/8~004/3~530\) proteins

Data

For PDB & SP proteins with sequence length in range \([40, 1000]\) have been considered. These sequences had GO annotations in the Molecular Function Ontology (MFO) with 17 different evidence codes.

Evaluation metrics

  • AUC
  • Maximum F-measure (\(F_{max}\)) (harmonic mean of the precision and recall)
  • Normalized semantic distance (\(S_{min}\))

Confidence intervals have been created using Bootstrap.

Results

Results - CAFA

Conclusions

  • Deep, pre-trained embeddings outperform hand-crafted sequence and structure representations
  • Simple models with good features beat complex models with one-hot encoded amino acid
  • GCN performs similarly to 1D-CNN when using ELMo embeddings
  • Protein structure does not add information to the ELMo embeddings
  • Language modeling learns a coarse functional representation
  • Supervised protein embeddings give insights into the behavior of the models
